item.description: Scientists have been using stem cells to grow tiny human brains for years in order to study the organ's development. In a historic first, hundreds of brain organoids grown in Petri dishes from donated human stem cells have sprouted symmetrical pairs of eyes. These rudimentary structures can not only sense the light around them, but send those signals to the rest of the organoid.
